# Interview Questions

## What is a Kubernetes Cluster?

A Kubernetes Cluster is a collection of Control Plane and Worker Nodes working together to deploy and manage containerized applications.

---

## What is the Control Plane?

The Control Plane is the brain of Kubernetes. It manages the cluster but does not run applications.

---

## What is a Worker Node?

A Worker Node is a server where Pods, containers and applications actually run.

---

## What is the API Server?

API Server is the entry point of Kubernetes. Every request first reaches the API Server.

---

## What is Scheduler?

Scheduler selects the best Worker Node to run newly created Pods.

---

## What is Controller Manager?

Controller Manager ensures the current state of the cluster always matches the desired state.

---

## What is etcd?

etcd is Kubernetes' distributed key-value database that stores all cluster information.

---

## What is kubelet?

kubelet runs on every Worker Node and communicates with the Control Plane to create and monitor Pods.

---

## What is kube-proxy?

kube-proxy manages networking and enables communication between Pods and Services.

---

## What is Container Runtime?

Container Runtime is responsible for pulling images and creating/running containers.

---

# Key Takeaways

✔ A Kubernetes Cluster is a group of servers, not another server.

✔ The Control Plane manages the cluster.

✔ Worker Nodes run Pods and applications.

✔ API Server is the entry point for all Kubernetes requests.

✔ Scheduler selects the Worker Node for Pods.

✔ Controller Manager maintains the desired state.

✔ etcd stores cluster information.

✔ kubelet manages Pods on each Worker Node.

✔ kube-proxy handles networking.

✔ Container Runtime creates and runs containers.

